list-item.p:
The formation (or nonformation) of a superordinate identity between workshop participants


mentioning (or not mentioning) broader overriding identity categories to which both Jewish–Israelis and Palestinians belong;



overt self-categorization—for both individuals and the group—in an overriding identity category;



an indication of preference for an overriding identity category over national identity.

Ethnocentric, confrontational behavior


blaming the other side for the conflict’s continuation while refraining from assigning responsibility or blame to one’s own side;



overt rejection of blame of one’s own side and ascription of blame to the other side.

Cooperative, nonethnocentric behavior


blaming one’s own side for the conflict’s continuation while justifying the other side’s behavior;



overt rejection of blame ascription to the other side and acceptance of blame and responsibility of one’s own side.
